The Latin American locust years
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Almost everywhere, the economic conditions are deteriorating, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
This is hardly surprising since the great majority of Latin American countries have spent the past twenty years going nowhere.
The capitals have been sold and the national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been eaten by locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual growth rate of GDP per capita in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this pace, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through timid wage increases?
The economic stagnation is due to a poor government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and very widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush to privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been sold at auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Ultimately, the revenues derived from privatization have produced little in the context of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Even worse, the liquidation of state property has been accompanied by massive foreign debt.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the loan made by national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency represents a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The influx of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When money stopped flowing, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of in-depth reforms, too few preliminary conditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that functioned along technocratic lines and considered economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed each other.
Institutions are being put on the ground, property rights are being questioned, and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more of a chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who lead the opinion polls in the period preceding the presidential elections in Brazil, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thought that capital has already begun to flee - even if the elections are just a few months away.
Democratization in Mexico has brought greater stability, but this might well prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance continues to deteriorate, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it's supposed to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate, which is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the financially speaking result, because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little base to accumulate capital and increase productivity.
Venezuela now sighs after the 1970s' oil-rich years of OPEC -- to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed instead of saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40 %, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are in favor of the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
You cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP only represents half of that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate of around 15 % per year in China's coastal region, which can seriously doubt that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil ?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to go smoothly, first due to the massive influx of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of accession to the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to deteriorate: governments are backtracking on reforms and the economy is losing ground to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were pouring in, but those times are largely over.
We must then expect even worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem - a presidential candidate in Argentina once again - may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
